FOREGROUND HERO — BAG (REFERENCE-LOCKED; MAXIMUM MATERIAL / COLOR / OPTICS)
Material class (name it exactly): A semi-translucent, milky-white woven polypropylene sack used for retail firewood — not agricultural orange / red / amber net, not open “cargo net” holes, not knitted string bag, not kraft paper, not solid opaque plastic sheeting.

Weave / texture (critical): The body is a fine-to-medium tight cross-hatch weave (warp and weft visible as a regular grid), much denser than construction safety mesh — the openings are small; from a normal viewing distance the surface reads as continuous white fabric with a subtle grid relief, not a fishnet. Individual strands are narrow, slightly flattened extruded tapes that interlace at clear crossover points (tiny knots / overlaps). Surface finish: matte — low specular; no glossy plastic shine, no wet look, no satin highlight streaks except very soft grazing light on weave ridges only.

Color of the plastic (body): Clean milky white — think frosted milk glass + white cotton — not pure optic bleached paper white in shadow (shadows go cool grey-white), not yellowed, not cream, not beige, not grey bag. Where backlight or strong rim light hits, the film reads brighter chalk white but still diffused, never transparent like glass.

Opacity / translucency (how light and wood read through): The wall of the sack behaves like a thin diffusing medium: you clearly perceive the silhouettes, bulk, and orientation of logs inside; you see broad color fields — dark bark masses vs pale split faces — forming a high-contrast vertical “striping” through the fabric. Fine bark micro-fissures are softened and slightly veiled; edges of logs are gentle, not razor-sharp as if the bag were absent. No “see-through window” clarity — if end grain reads, it should look slightly milky, not HD through air. No double-exposure ghost unless subtle real moiré from weave vs sensor (optional).

Mechanical interaction with contents (shape language): The sack is rammed full of large split firewood. The fabric is stretched taut over hard corners and cylindrical faces of logs, producing: sharp tension creases along edges where wood presses the wall; broad smooth bulges over rounded faces; irregular vertical undulations — the column is not a perfect cuboid. Side silhouette: lumpy organic, not straight ruler edges.

Top construction — header & handle: The upper band is a separate, more opaque white reinforced header (thicker plastic strip / folded hem look): flatter, more “solid white” than the body, less wood detail bleeding through (only faint bulk darkness possible). Centered die-cut carrying handle: a horizontal oval slot punched through the header — smooth inner cut edge, slightly bevelled, no cracks, no secondary reinforcement ring unless minimal moulded thickness. Header top edge is clean machine straight; transition from header to woven body is a sharp horizontal seam line (heat weld / stitch impression allowed, subtle).

Bottom & stance: Flat stable base so the pack stands upright on patio/wood bed. Bottom corners subtly flare / bell outward under compressive weight of logs (plastic fatigue look very mild, not torn). No standing on a single point; full footprint contact.

Contents (what must read through the milky weave): Approximately 5–6 large split logs stacked horizontally (lengths mostly parallel, filling width). Bark: charcoal grey to deep earthy brown, rough ridged plates, deep shadow in grooves. Split faces / interiors: light tan to pale beige, visible grain, not neon yellow, not orange-stained interior as the default — the signature look is dark bark vs pale split-face contrast creating stripes through the white fabric. End discs may appear as soft muted ovals through the sack.

Lighting interaction (photographic): Soft specular breakup only on weave high points; shadow side of bag cools to blue-grey white; fire glow may tint only the lower 10–20% of the sack with warm amber spill on the plastic while the plastic itself stays white (tint = lighting, not dyed orange material).

